    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from scipy.integrate import solve_ivp\n",
    "\n",
    "def f(x, y):\n",
    "    return (2 - 2 * x * y) / (x**2 + 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def true_solution(x):\n",
    "    return (2 * x + 1) / (x**2 + 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Euler method\n",
    "def euler_method(f, x_span, y0, h):\n",
    "    x_values = np.arange(x_span[0], x_span[1] + h, h)\n",
    "    y_values = np.zeros(len(x_values))\n",
    "    y_values[0] = y0\n",
    "    for i in range(1, len(x_values)):\n",
    "        y_values[i] = y_values[i-1] + h * f(x_values[i-1], y_values[i-1])\n",
    "    return x_values, y_values\n",
    "\n",
    "x_span = (0, 1)\n",
    "y0 = 1\n",
    "h = 0.1\n",
    "\n",
    "# Solve using the(RK2 and RK4)\n",
    "sol_rk2 = solve_ivp(f, x_span, [y0], method='RK23', t_eval=np.arange(0, 1+h, h))\n",
    "sol_rk4 = solve_ivp(f, x_span, [y0], method='RK45', t_eval=np.arange(0, 1+h, h))\n",
    "# Solve using Euler's method\n",
    "x_euler, y_euler = euler_method(f, x_span, y0, h)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compute the true solution\n",
    "x_true = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)\n",
    "y_true = true_solution(x_true)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the results\n",
    "plt.plot(x_euler, y_euler, 'o-', label='Euler method', markersize=4)\n",
    "plt.plot(sol_rk2.t, sol_rk2.y[0], 's-', label='2nd order Runge-Kutta', markersize=4)\n",
    "plt.plot(sol_rk4.t, sol_rk4.y[0], '^-', label='4th order Runge-Kutta', markersize=4)\n",
    "plt.plot(x_true, y_true, '-', label='True solution')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Numerical Solutions of ODE')\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compute and tabulate relative errors in percentage points\n",
    "true_y_at_x_euler = true_solution(x_euler)\n",
    "true_y_at_x_rk2 = true_solution(sol_rk2.t)\n",
    "true_y_at_x_rk4 = true_solution(sol_rk4.t)\n",
    "\n",
    "error_euler = np.abs((true_y_at_x_euler - y_euler) / true_y_at_x_euler) * 100\n",
    "error_rk2 = np.abs((true_y_at_x_rk2 - sol_rk2.y[0]) / true_y_at_x_rk2) * 100\n",
    "error_rk4 = np.abs((true_y_at_x_rk4 - sol_rk4.y[0]) / true_y_at_x_rk4) * 100\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Euler Method:\")\n",
    "print(\"Y_euler:\",y_euler)\n",
    "print(\"True y-values:\", true_y_at_x_euler)\n",
    "print(\"Euler method errors (%):\", error_euler)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"2nd Order Runge-Kutta Method:\")\n",
    "print(\"Y_rk2_values:\", sol_rk2.y[0])\n",
    "print(\"True y-values:\", true_y_at_x_rk2)\n",
    "print(\"RK2 method errors (%):\", error_rk2)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"4th Order Runge-Kutta Method:\")\n",
    "print(\"Y_rk4_values:\", sol_rk4.y[0])\n",
    "print(\"True y-values:\", true_y_at_x_rk4)\n",
    "print(\"RK4 method errors (%):\", error_rk4)"

    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate random numbers from a normal distribution\n",
    "mean = 0\n",
    "std_dev = 10\n",
    "sample_size = 100000\n",
    "random_numbers = np.random.normal(mean, std_dev, sample_size)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot histogram of the sample\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))\n",
    "plt.hist(random_numbers, bins=100, density=True, alpha=0.6, color='g', label='Sample Histogram')\n",
    "plt.title('Histogram of Sample')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Value')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Frequency')\n",
    "# Plot parent distribution\n",
    "x = np.linspace(-50, 50, 1000)\n",
    "parent_distribution = 1/(std_dev * np.sqrt(2 * np.pi)) * np.exp(-(x - mean)**2 / (2 * std_dev**2))\n",
    "plt.plot(x, parent_distribution, linewidth=2, color='r', label='Parent Distribution')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

   "source": [
    "Given that the sample data is generated from a normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 10, we expect the data to exhibit variability across different frequency components without any dominant frequencies. This expectation arises from the nature of the normal distribution, which produces random data points with a bell-shaped curve. In the frequency domain, this translates to a power spectrum that is evenly distributed across different wavevector (k) bins, without any single bin significantly dominating the others. Therefore, when we plot the power spectrum, we observe a relatively flat distribution without pronounced peaks, confirming the absence of strong periodicities or dominant frequencies in the data. This observation is consistent with the expected behavior of random data sampled from a normal distribution, where variability is spread out across the frequency spectrum rather than concentrated at specific frequencies.\n"

    "## Q_7 \n",
    "1. *Storage of Input Data:*\n",
    "   - A billion numbers, each a double-precision floating-point number (8 bytes):\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     10^9 \\text{ numbers} \\times 8 \\text{ bytes/number} = 8 \\times 10^9 \\text{ bytes} = 8 \\text{ GB}\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "2. *Storage for Output Data:*\n",
    "   - The output of an FFT on real data is complex numbers. Each complex number (real + imaginary) is 16 bytes:\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     10^9 \\text{ complex numbers} \\times 16 \\text{ bytes/complex number} = 16 \\times 10^9 \\text{ bytes} = 16 \\text{ GB}\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "\n",
    "3. *Temporary Storage:*\n",
    "   - Temporary storage for the FFT computation often requires an additional amount of memory on the order of the input size. In this case, another 8 GB:\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     8 \\text{ GB}\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "\n",
    "Total memory required is:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "8 \\text{ GB (input data)} + 16 \\text{ GB (output data)} + 8 \\text{ GB (temporary storage)} = 32 \\text{ GB}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Number of Computers Needed\n",
    "\n",
    "Given that each computer has 4 GB of memory:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\frac{32 \\text{ GB}}{4 \\text{ GB/computer}} = 8 \\text{ computers}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For distributed FFT computation, the following libraries can be used:\n",
    "\n",
    " *MPI (Message Passing Interface)*:\n",
    "   - *mpi4py* is the Python binding for MPI and is useful for parallel and distributed computing tasks.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n"
   ]

    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "xmin = -15\n",
    "xmax = 15\n",
    "n = 1024\n",
    "x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, n)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def f(x):\n",
    "    return np.exp(-2 * np.abs(x))\n",
    "\n",
    "def analytical_ft(k):\n",
    "    return np.sqrt(8/np.pi)*(1 / (k**2 + 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "f_x= f(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compute Fourier transform\n",
    "ft_k = np.fft.fft(f_x,norm='ortho')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Frequency values\n",
    "freq =2*np.pi* np.fft.fftfreq(n, d=(xmax-xmin)/n)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Normalization factor\n",
    "dx = (xmax - xmin) / (n)\n",
    "norm_factor = dx*np.sqrt(n / (2 * np.pi))*np.exp(-1j*freq*xmin)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Multiply Fourier transform by normalization factor\n",
    "new_ft_k = ft_k*norm_factor\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the sinc function and its Fourier transform\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)\n",
    "plt.plot(x, f_x,'c.-',label='f(x)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('f(x)')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)\n",
    "plt.scatter(freq,analytical_ft(freq),s=10,color='r',label='analytical fourier transform')\n",
    "plt.plot(freq, np.abs(new_ft_k),color='g',label='numerical fourier transform')\n",
    "plt.title('Fourier Transform of f(x)=exp(-2|x|) Function')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Frequency')\n",
    "plt.ylabel(r'$F(k_{q})$')\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the real part of the Fourier transform\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
    "plt.plot(freq, new_ft_k.real, label='Numerical (Real)', linestyle='--')\n",
    "plt.scatter(freq, analytical_ft(freq).real,s=10,color='b', label='Analytical (Real)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('k')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Real Part')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Real Part of Fourier Transform')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the imaginary part of the Fourier transform\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
    "plt.plot(freq, new_ft_k.imag, label='Numerical (Imaginary)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('k')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Imaginary Part')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

    "## Q_10 Relationship Between Real and Imaginary Parts of the Fourier Transform\n",
    "\n",
    "The relationship between the real and imaginary parts of the Fourier transform can be understood through the properties of Fourier transforms of real-valued functions:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. *Symmetry Properties*:\n",
    "   - *Even/Odd Functions*: For a real-valued function \\( f(x) \\), if \\( f(x) \\) is even, the Fourier transform \\( F(k) \\) will have a real part that is even and an imaginary part that is odd.\n",
    "   - *Real Functions*: For any real-valued function \\( f(x) \\), the real part of its Fourier transform is an even function, and the imaginary part is an odd function.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. *Conjugate Symmetry*:\n",
    "   - For real-valued functions, the Fourier transform \\( F(k) \\) exhibits conjugate symmetry: \\( F(-k) = \\overline{F(k)} \\). This means that the real part of \\( F(k) \\) is symmetric (even), and the imaginary part is antisymmetric (odd).\n",
    "\n",
    "In simpler terms:\n",
    "\n",
    "- *Evenness and Oddness*: The real part of the Fourier transform of a real-valued function is even (symmetric around zero), and the imaginary part is odd (antisymmetric around zero).\n",
    "- *Mutual Determination*: The real and imaginary parts of the Fourier transform are interconnected. Knowing one can help you determine the other through the Hilbert transform.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The real part of the Fourier transform (left plot) is even and matches the analytical solution because the function \\( \\exp(-2|x|) \\) is even.\n",
    "- The imaginary part of the Fourier transform (right plot) is ideally zero (or close to zero) because the function \\( \\exp(-2|x|) \\) is even and real-valued, leading to no odd imaginary component."
   ]
